Then you will absolutely love Haskell's and Ocaml's standard libraries (if you can spare some CPU cycles).  Paranoid static typing with easy genericness (more flexible than C++ templates), and they don't have the one show stopping flaw C++'s <algorithm> still have sometimes: lack of locality. Until C++ has closures, a loop will often look like this:<p><pre><code>    body(…){ code_of_body; }
    fun(…)
    {
      // (Big) blob of code
      std::loop(begin, end, body)
      …
    }
</code></pre>
I have done it. Lack of locality <i>kills</i> readability, so I still use loops even when std::accumulate or std::foreach would do.
